\begin_layout Subsection
Similarity
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Separating the matrix calculations of the preceding discussion from their
 geometric interpretation, we have been examining matrices 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 related by the equation
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
B=P^{-1}AP,
\]

\end_inset

a relation known as 
\series bold
similarity
\series default
.
 Indeed, matrices 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 are called 
\series bold
similar
\series default
 if 
\begin_inset Formula $B=P^{-1}AP$
\end_inset

 (or equivalently 
\begin_inset Formula $PBP^{-1}=A$
\end_inset

).
 Consistent with the name, matrices related this way share a number of similar
 features.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
If matrices 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 are similar, then 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 have the same (i) determinant, (ii) eigenvalues, and (iii) rank.
\end_layout

