\begin_layout Standard
Another important feature of similar matrices is that powers of similar
 matrices are similar.
 That is, if 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 are square and similar, then 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{k}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B^{k}$
\end_inset

 are similar, where the 
\begin_inset Formula $k^{th}$
\end_inset

 power of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is defined by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
M^{k}=\overset{k\text{ times}}{\overbrace{M\cdot M\cdots M}}
\]

\end_inset

(analogous to powers of real numbers).
 To see that this is true, write 
\begin_inset Formula $A=PBP^{-1}$
\end_inset

 and compute
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
A^{k} & =(PBP^{-1})^{k}\\
 & =\overset{k\text{ times}}{\overbrace{PBP^{-1}\cdot PBP^{-1}\cdots PBP^{-1}}}\\
 & =\overset{k\text{ times}}{P\overbrace{B\cdot B\cdots B}}P^{-1}\\
 & =PB^{k}P^{-1}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

This is particularly useful when 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is similar to a diagonal matrix.
 In this case, 
\begin_inset Formula $A=PDP^{-1}$
\end_inset

 for a diagonal matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
A^{k} & =PD^{k}P^{-1}\\
 & =P\left[\begin{array}{cccc}
D_{1,1} & 0 & \cdots & 0\\
0 & D_{2,2} & \cdots & 0\\
\vdots & \vdots & \ddots & \vdots\\
0 & 0 & \cdots & D_{n,n}
\end{array}\right]^{k}P^{-1}\\
 & =P\left[\begin{array}{cccc}
D_{1,1}^{k} & 0 & \cdots & 0\\
0 & D_{2,2}^{k} & \cdots & 0\\
\vdots & \vdots & \ddots & \vdots\\
0 & 0 & \cdots & D_{n,n}^{k}
\end{array}\right]P^{-1}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

so the difficulty in raising 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 to any power is commensurate with the difficulty of raising 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

 to that power.
 Earlier we found that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left[\begin{array}{cc}
-7 & -4\\
6 & 7
\end{array}\right]=\left[\begin{array}{cc}
-2 & 1\\
1 & -3
\end{array}\right]\left[\begin{array}{cc}
-5 & 0\\
0 & 5
\end{array}\right]\left[\begin{array}{cc}
-\frac{3}{5} & -\frac{1}{5}\\
-\frac{1}{5} & -\frac{2}{5}
\end{array}\right]
\]

\end_inset

so 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\left[\begin{array}{cc}
-7 & -4\\
6 & 7
\end{array}\right]^{5} & =\left[\begin{array}{cc}
-2 & 1\\
1 & -3
\end{array}\right]\left[\begin{array}{cc}
-5 & 0\\
0 & 5
\end{array}\right]^{5}\left[\begin{array}{cc}
-\frac{3}{5} & -\frac{1}{5}\\
-\frac{1}{5} & -\frac{2}{5}
\end{array}\right]\\
 & =\left[\begin{array}{cc}
-2 & 1\\
1 & -3
\end{array}\right]\left[\begin{array}{cc}
-3125 & 0\\
0 & 3125
\end{array}\right]\left[\begin{array}{cc}
-\frac{3}{5} & -\frac{1}{5}\\
-\frac{1}{5} & -\frac{2}{5}
\end{array}\right]\\
 & =\left[\begin{array}{cc}
-4375 & -2500\\
3750 & 4375
\end{array}\right].
\end{align*}

\end_inset

While that may not be the most pleasant computation, it certainly beats
 computing 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left[\begin{array}{cc}
-7 & -4\\
6 & 7
\end{array}\right]^{5}=\left[\begin{array}{cc}
-7 & -4\\
6 & 7
\end{array}\right]\left[\begin{array}{cc}
-7 & -4\\
6 & 7
\end{array}\right]\left[\begin{array}{cc}
-7 & -4\\
6 & 7
\end{array}\right]\left[\begin{array}{cc}
-7 & -4\\
6 & 7
\end{array}\right]\left[\begin{array}{cc}
-7 & -4\\
6 & 7
\end{array}\right]
\]

\end_inset

directly.
 This property of similar matrices is at the heart of the power method for
 estimating eigenvalues (section 
