\begin_layout Standard
When a matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is similar to a diagonal matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

, we say that 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
diagonalizable
\series default
 and that the matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $P^{-1}MP=D$
\end_inset

 
\series bold
diagonalizes
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 We saw earlier that if 
\begin_inset Formula $P^{-1}MP=D$
\end_inset

 then the columns of 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 are eigenvectors.
 We shall now add the observation that the eigenvectors (columns of 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

) must be linearly independent, a requirement for 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 to be invertible.
 On the other hand, if 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is an 
\begin_inset Formula $n\times n$
\end_inset

 matrix admitting 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 linearly independent eigenvectors, then 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is diagonalizable and 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

, a matrix whose columns are 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 linearly independent eigenvectors of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

, diagonalizes 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
P^{-1}MP & =P^{-1}\left[\begin{array}{cccc}
\lambda_{1}P_{:,1} & \lambda_{2}P_{:,2} & \cdots & \lambda_{n}P_{:,n}\end{array}\right]\\
 & =P^{-1}P\left[\begin{array}{cccc}
\lambda_{1} & 0 & \cdots & 0\\
0 & \lambda_{2} & \cdots & 0\\
\vdots & \vdots & \ddots & \vdots\\
0 & 0 & \cdots & \lambda_{n}
\end{array}\right]\\
 & =\left[\begin{array}{cccc}
\lambda_{1} & 0 & \cdots & 0\\
0 & \lambda_{2} & \cdots & 0\\
\vdots & \vdots & \ddots & \vdots\\
0 & 0 & \cdots & \lambda_{n}
\end{array}\right],
\end{align*}

\end_inset

which is diagonal.
 Altogether, an 
\begin_inset Formula $n\times n$
\end_inset

 matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is diagonalizable if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 has 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 linearly independent eigenvectors.
\end_layout

